<https://colonial-heritage.triply.cc/nmvw/id/object/RV-2732-38> <https://colonialcollections.nl/schema#description> "Wendat cigar case; late 19th century\r\nBirchbark, moosehair, porcupine quills, pigments; 14 x 7 cm.\r\nRMV 2732-38; donated by widow of P.J. Bruining-Lindo (unidentified), 1948\r\n\r\n\tThe fine arts of the Wendat First Nation of Quebec, as known through complex, brilliantly colored designs on clothing and ceremonial objects, were admired by Europeans from the early days of contact in the seventeenth century. The Wendat birch bark souvenir wares of the nineteenth century, such as this vibrant, moosehair-embroidered cigar case, represent continuity of these traditions, integrated with new forms and motifs. Embellished with figural images, it is an example of the Wendat works made for European travelers, highly sought after mementos of a visit to Canada. \r\n\tThe Wendat (formerly referred to as Huron), were known for their traditions of commerce and diplomacy and from the seventeenth century built strong relations with the French and then English newcomers. The Wendat souvenir arts developed through these connections, in the intercultural exchange between women of Indigenous communities and the French convents of Quebec. Drawing from both arts traditions, Aboriginal materials, techniques, and forms came together with European pictorial representation in new modes of artistic expression. Women of both the convent and Indigenous communities produced the moosehair embroidered bark souvenirs. While less is known about the eighteenth century production, believed to have been made by the Quebec convents, the Wendat bark work of the nineteenth century has a distinct style, It is found in museums in Europe and North America. There are several Wendat works with provenance and these examples assist in making attributions.\r\nThe Wendat souvenir arts contained significance and meaning for both their Wendat creators and Europeans buyers (Phillips 1998:20). To the Wendat, souvenir works were an important source of income and in addition, they were a site for the expression of Wendat cultural traditions and identity. Bird motifs such as the images of this cigar case, larger-than-life size, were characteristic of Wendat work and may have held meanings based in Great Lakes oral traditions. In these narratives, birds held a special significance, they could be otherworldly beings, a form into which the soul transformed itself (Hamell 1988:9,11,14,16). With this understanding, the Wendat bark work scenes can be interpreted as visual depictions of figures from the oral tradition. \r\n\r\n\tTo European buyers the materials of moosehair and birch bark and their Indigenous makers suggested the exotic, a reminder of a visit to what was seen then as a new world. In addition, in the period of European industrialization and urbanization, motifs depicting a simpler life close to nature may have held an anti-modernist appeal. Vignettes such as those of the cigar case, depicting traditional everyday life in camp scenes of a cooking pot hanging over a fire, a woman walking in the woodland carrying her pipe, wearing traditional Wendat dress of patterned over-shirt and leggings, may have represented to Europeans an imagined pre-industrial world.\r\n\r\nStylistic analysis and study of the dyes used in the moosehair help to date this work. The sharp yellow color was produced with picric acid, used as a dying agent from around 1849, while the mauve color was produced from aniline dye that came into use around 1859, providing the earliest possible date. Stylistic comparison with works in dated collections suggests that the cigar case was made in the 1870s or1880s. While earlier Wendat figural works focused on the detail of dress, trees, and flowers, this work shows a new sense of design and fresh aesthetic direction that is characteristic of works of the 1870s and later. \r\n\r\nThe Wendat figural motifs of this era had moved to a more stylized form of representation, with fewer elements and a limited color palette in the bright chemical dyes that were then popular. The cigar case has four fields of design, the two sides of its base and the two sides of its lid, with the motifs placed in careful arrangement. Structured in blocks of colour, the motifs on the cigar case top mirror and balance those of the base in form and line and are arranged in patterns to create a sense of rhythm and movement. This produces a harmonious composition within each field and in the unity of all four, with the balanced asymmetry that was characteristic of Wendat work. Intrinsically dynamic, bringing together Aboriginal and European visual arts, this Wendat cigar box demonstrates the continuity of its makers’ cultural traditions and their enduring appeal.\r\n\r\nAnne de Stecher\r\nCarleton University, Ottawa\r\n\r\nGeorge Hamell, Trading Metaphors: The Magic of Beads; in: Proceedings of the 1982 Glass Trade Bead Conference; Rochester Museum and Science Center; Rochester, NY, 1988. Ruth Phillips, Trading Identities; McGill-Queen’s University Press; Montreal and Kingston, 1998.\r\n\r\nDoosje van berkenbast, geborduurd met geverfd elandshaar. Motieven zijn een vrouw, enkele haardplaatsen en een vogel. Een typisch product voor de toeristenmarkt.\r\nBoombast, met name berkenbast, was een product dat het gehele jaar door in het gehele noordoostelijk cultuurgebied beschikbaar was en derhalve voor vele doeleinden werd gebruikt. Hutten werden bedekt met stroken boombast of matten gevlochten van boombastvezels. Van deze vezels werden ook kleding en tassen gemaakt. De houten spanten van kano's werden van een berkenbast laag voorzien. Voor het verzamelen, vervoeren, bewaren en bereiden van voedsel gebruikte men dozen van boombast, in allerlei modellen en maten, afhankelijk van het gebruik. Na de komst van de blanken werden dozen en andere soorten containers van berkenbast (bijv. brievenmappen, sigarenkokers, briletuis, theemutsen, naaimanden, e.d.) een belangrijk handelsartikel, zowel voor dagelijks gebruik (onversierd) als voor de sier. De dozen werden meestal versierd door borduurwerk met geverfde stekelvarkenspennen of geverfd elandshaar. Soms zijn het geometrische motieven, maar meestal bloemen, bladeren en afbeeldingen van personen. Door het wegkrabben van de bovenste bastlaag wordt de donkerder onderlaag zichtbaar, een \"scraffitto-techniek\" waarmee patronen op dozen werden aangebracht. Een nieuwe markt ontstond door de toeristenindustrie, en Niagara Falls werd een centrum voor de handel in Indiaanse souvenirs, met name met pennenwerk en elandshaar versierde berkenbast doosjes en miniatuur-kano's, maar ook onderzetters, fotolijstjes, speldenkussens, e.d. Deze markt levert tot op vandaag een belangrijke bijdrage aan het levensonderhoud van Indiaanse gezinnen uit het noordoostelijk cultuurgebied." .
